s |nfl=2495252 |espn=14140 |pfr=W/WrigK.00}}\n* [http://www.mstateathletics.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=16800&ATCLID=1087911 Mississippi State Bulldogs bio]\n\n{{Seahawks2011DraftPicks}}\n{{Super Bowl XLVIII}}\n{{Seattle Seahawks roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wright, K. J.}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American players of American football]]\n[[Category:American football linebackers]]\n[[Category:Mississippi State Bulldogs football players]]\n[[Category:National Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:People from Olive Branch, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Seattle Seahawks players]]\n[[Category:Super Bowl champions]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football linebacker}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{infobox NFL player\n|name=K. J. Wright\n|image=K. J. Wright.JPG\n|image_size=275\n|caption=Wright with the Seattle Seahawks\n|current_team=Seattle Seahawks\n|number=50\n|position=[[Outside linebacker]]\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1989|07|23|mf=y}}\n|birth_place=[[Olive Branch, Mississippi]]\n|height_ft=6\n|height_in=4\n|weight_lbs=246\n|high_school=[[Olive Branch High School (Olive Branch, Mississippi)|Olive Branch]]<br/>([[Olive Branch, Mississippi]])\n|college=[[Mississippi State Bulldogs football|Mississippi State]]\n|draftyear=2011\n|draftround=4\n|draftpick=99\n|pastteams=\n* [[Seattle Seahawks]] ({{NFL Year|2011}}\u2013present)\n|status=Active\n|highlights=\n* [[Super Bowl|Super Bowl champion]] ([[Super Bowl XLVIII|XLVIII]])\n* [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2017 Pro Bowl|2016]])\n|statweek=\n|statseason=2019\n|statlabel1=[[Tackle (gridiron football position)|Total tackles]]\n|statvalue1=855\n|statlabel2=[[Quarterback sacks|Sacks]]\n|statvalue2=11.5\n|statlabel3=[[Interceptions]]\n|statvalue3=5\n|statlabel4=[[Fumble|Forced fumbles]]\n|statvalue4=10\n|statlabel5=[[Fumble|Fumble recoveries]]\n|statvalue5=7\n| statlabel6    = [[Pass deflected|Pass deflections]]\n| statvalue6    = 44\n|nfl=WRI487649\n|pfr=W/WrigK.00\n}}\n\n'''Kenneth Bernard Wright, Jr.''' (born July 23, 1989) is an [[American football]] [[linebacker]] for the [[Seattle Seahawks]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He was drafted by the Seahawks in the fourth round of the [[2011 NFL Draft]].<ref name=\"Seahawks.com\">[http://www.seahawks.com/team/roster/K.J.-Wright/d5b919c0-1ed5-40df-b031-e9bbd9757351 Seahawks Seahawks: K.J. Wright] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120131164854/http://www.seahawks.com/team/roster/K.J.-Wright/d5b919c0-1ed5-40df-b031-e9bbd9757351 |date=January 31, 2012 }}</ref> He played [[college football]] at [[Mississippi State Bulldogs football|Mississippi State]].\n\n==High school career==\nWright attended [[Olive Branch High School (Olive Branch, Mississippi)|Olive Branch High School]] in [[Olive Branch, Mississippi]], where he was a three-sport athlete in football, basketball and track. He was named first-team, all-state on the defensive line by ''[[The Clarion-Ledger]]''. He recorded 91 total tackles during his senior season in which 48 of them were solo tackles. He was listed as the number 19 prospect in Mississippi following his senior season according to Rivals.com.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mississippi State Bio: K.J. Wright|url=http://www.hailstate.com/ViewArscholarshipticle.dbml?SPSID=90891&SPID=10997&DB_LANG=C&DB_OEM_ID=16800&ATCLID=1087911&Q_SEASON=2010|work=Official State of the Mississippi State Bulldogs}}{{dead link|date=April 2012}}</ref> He was awarded with his performance with top scholarship offers from [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]], [[Arkansas Razorbacks football|Arkansas]], [[Ole Miss Rebels football|Ole Miss]], and [[South Carolina Gamecocks football|South Carolina]]. He committed to [[Mississippi State Bulldogs football|Mississippi State]] during his senior year of high school.\n\n==College career==\nWright played for Mississippi State during his college career. He held onto the number 34 while playing for Mississippi State and played the [[linebacker]] position. During his sophomore season, he was promoted as a starter on the defensive unit as an outside linebacker. He then began to start for the rest of his college career except for his senior year, when he did not start for two games due to formation changes. He still started ten out of twelve games during his senior year.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Season !! {{tooltip|GP|Games played}} !! {{tooltip|GS|Games started}} !! Tackles !! Sacks !! {{tooltip|PD|Passes defensed}} !! {{tooltip|FF|Forced fumbles}} !! {{tooltip|Hurries|Quarterback hurries}}\n|-\n| 2007 || 10 || 0 || 7 || 4 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| 2008 || 12 || 12|| 72 || 4 || 3 || 1 || 3\n|-\n| 2009 || 12 || 10 || 81 || 2 || 2 || 1 || 4\n|-\n| 2010 || 13 || 13 || 98 || 4 || 9 || 1 || 4\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\nOn January 13, 2011, it was announced Wright had accepted his invitation to play in the [[2011 Senior Bowl]] and was one of four Mississippi State players attending, including [[Derek Sherrod]], [[Pernell McPhee]] and [[Chris White (linebacker)|Chris White]].<ref>{{cite web| title=Vancleave's White one of four Mississippi State players invited to Senior Bowl| url=http://blog.gulflive.com/mississippi-press-sports/2011/01/vancleaves_white_one_of_four_m.html| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=blog.gulflive.com| date=January 14, 2011}}</ref> On January 29, 2011, he played in the [[Senior Bowl|Under Armour's Senior Bowl]] and was part of [[2011 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills']] head coach [[Chan Gailey|Chan Gailey's]] South team that defeated the North 24\u201310. He attended the [[NFL Scouting Combine]] in [[Indianapolis, Indiana]] and completed all of the combine drills. On March 10, 2011, Wright attended Mississippi State's pro day and opted to perform all of the drills except the broad jump and bench press. He was able to beat his times in the 40-yard dash (4.71 seconds), 20-yard dash (2.69 seconds), and 10-yard dash (1.66 seconds) from the NFL combine. At the conclusion of the pre-draft process, Wright was projected to be a third round pick by NFL draft experts and scouts. He was ranked the eighth best outside linebacker prospect in the draft by NFLDraftScout.com.<ref>{{cite web| title=K. J. Wright, DS #8 OLB, Mississippi State| url=http://www.nfldraftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=72570&draftyear=2011&genpos=OLB| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=nfldraftscout.com}}</ref>\n{{NFL predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 3\u215c\n|       weight = 246\n|         dash = 4.75\n|    ten split = 1.69\n| twenty split = 2.78\n|      shuttle = 4.46\n|   cone drill = 7.26\n|     vertical = 32\n|     broad ft = 10\n|     broad in = 0\n|        bench = 20\n|    wonderlic = \n|     arm span = 34\u215e\n|    hand span = 9\n|         note = All values from [[NFL Combine]]<ref>{{cite web| title=NFL Draft Profile: K. J. Wright| url=http://www.nfl.com/combine/profiles/k.j.-wright?id=2495252| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=nfl.com}}</ref>\n}}\nThe [[Seattle Seahawks]] selected Wright in the fourth round (99th overall) of the [[2011 NFL Draft]]. He was the 13th linebacker selected.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2011/draft.htm |title=2011 NFL Draft Listing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=2019-02-26}}</ref> General manager [[John Schneider (American football executive)|John Schneider]] and head coach [[Pete Carroll]] stated they liked the thought of Wright as a strong side linebacker with the possibility of playing rush linebacker.<ref name=\"star\">{{cite web| title=Former Mississippi State star K.J. Wright making early impression with Seattle Seahawks| url=http://blog.gulflive.com/mississippi-press-sports/2011/08/former_mississippi_state_star.html| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=blog.gulflive.com| author=Associated Press| date=August 23, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===2011===\nOn July 29, 2011, the Seahawks signed Wright to a four-year, [[United States dollar|$]]2.52 million [[contract]] that included a [[signing bonus]] of $486,000.<ref name=\"spotrac\">{{cite web| title=Spotrac.com: K. J. Wright contract| url=http://www.spotrac.com/nfl/seattle-seahawks/k.j.-wright-7818/| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=spotrac.com}}</ref>\n\nWright performed well and impressed coaches throughout training camp and began taking reps at middle linebacker after the unexpected release of [[Lofa Tatupu]] in July.<ref name=\"star\"/> Linebackers coach [[Ken Norton]] stated that he thought Wright was better suited for middle linebacker due to his instincts and length. He also felt that learning the position would speed up Wright's development since he would have to learn all of the defensive calls.<ref name=\"Curry\"/> Head coach Carroll named Wright the backup middle linebacker to veteran [[David Hawthorne]] to begin the 2011 regular season.<ref>{{cite web| title=Seahawks' Depth Chart Vs. San Francisco| url=https://www.blog.seattlepi.com/football/2011/09/07/seahawks-depth-chart-vs-san-francisco/amp/| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=blog.seattlepi.com| author=Christian Caple| date=September 7, 2011| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180914132400/https://blog.seattlepi.com/football/2011/09/07/seahawks-depth-chart-vs-san-francisco/amp/| archive-date=September 14, 2018| url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHe made his professional regular season debut and first career start in the [[2011 Seattle Seahawks season|Seahawks']] season-opener at the [[2011 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]] and recorded five combined tackles during the 33\u201317 loss. Wright earned the start at middle linebacker in place of Hawthorne, who was inactive due to a knee injury.<ref>{{cite web| title=John Carlson speaks about his shoulder injury, plus other notes| url=http://blog.seattlepi.com/football/2011/08/31/john-carlson-speaks-about-his-shoulder-injury-plus-other-notes/| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=blog.seattlepi.com| author=Christian Caple| date=August 31, 2011}}</ref> On September 22, 2011, Wright began practicing at weak side linebacker with the first team defense in practice. It was suspected he had supplanted [[Aaron Curry (American football)|Aaron Curry]] as the starting strong side linebacker after Curry had a dismal performance where he dropped a crucial interception in the second quarter of the Seahawks' 24\u20130 loss to the [[2011 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]] in Week 2.<ref>{{cite web|last=Williams|first=Eric|title=LB Aaron Curry demoted in favor of K.J. Wright|url=http://blog.thenewstribune.com/seahawks/2011/09/22/lb-aaron-curry-demoted-in-favor-of-k-j-wright/|work=LB Aaron Curry demoted in favor of K.J. Wright|publisher=The News Tribune|accessdate=January 24, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170415132535/http://blog.thenewstribune.com/seahawks/2011/09/22/lb-aaron-curry-demoted-in-favor-of-k-j-wright/|archive-date=April 15, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The next day, defensive coordinator [[Gus Bradley]] announced there would be a competition between Wright and Curry for the job as the starting strong side linebacker.<ref name=\"Curry\">{{cite web| title=LB Aaron Curry demoted in favor of K.J. Wright| url=http://blog.thenewstribune.com/seahawks/2011/09/22/lb-aaron-curry-demoted-in-favor-of-k-j-wright/| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=blog.thenewstribune.com| author=Eric Williams| date=September 22, 2011| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170415132535/http://blog.thenewstribune.com/seahawks/2011/09/22/lb-aaron-curry-demoted-in-favor-of-k-j-wright/| archive-date=April 15, 2017| url-status=dead| df=mdy-all}}</ref> On October 2, 2011, Wright earned his first career start at strong side linebacker after [[Matt McCoy (American football)|Matt McCoy]] started the previous week. He recorded two solo tackles in the 30\u201328 loss to the [[2011 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]]. Although he earned the start, he shared playing time with Curry, with Curry receiving more snaps. The following day, head coach Carroll stated that the competition for the starting strong side linebacker job between both players remained open.<ref>{{cite web| title=LB Matt McCoy out for \u201ca while\u201d but not the season, and other Monday notes| url=https://www.heraldnet.com/sports/lb-matt-mccoy-out-for-a-while-but-not-the-season-and-other-monday-notes/| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=heraldnet.com| author=John Boyle| date=October 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn Week 5, Wright made his second consecutive start at outside linebacker and made four combined tackles in a 36\u201325 victory at the [[2011 New York Giants season|New York Giants]]. On October 13, 2011, the Seahawks traded Curry to the [[2011 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]], effectively making Wright the ''de facto'' starting strong side linebacker for the remainder of the season.<ref>{{cite web| title=Seahawks ship Aaron Curry to Oakland| url=http://sportspressnw.com/2111541/2011/seahawks-reportedly-ship-aaron-curry-to-oakland| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=sportspressnw.com| date=October 12, 2011}}</ref> On December 1, 2011, he collected five solo tackles and made his first career sack on [[2011 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles']] quarterback [[Vince Young]] during a 31\u201314 victory.<ref>{{cite web| title=NFL Game Center: Week 13-2011: Philadelphia Eagles @ Seattle Seahawks| url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2011120100/2011/REG13/eagles@seahawks| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=nfl.com}}</ref> The following game, he recorded a season-high eight combined tackles and sacked [[Sam Bradford]] during a 30\u201313 win over the [[2011 St. Louis Rams season|St. Louis Rams]]. On December 18, 2011, Wright recorded a season-high eight combined tackles during a 38\u201314 victory at the [[2011 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]]. He finished his rookie season with 65 combined tackles (50 solo), three pass deflections, and two sacks in 16 games and 12 starts.<ref>{{cite web| title=NFL Player stats: K. J. Wright (2011)| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/k.j.wright/2495252/gamelogs?season=2011| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\n===2012===\nWright returned as the starting strong side linebacker in 2012, alongside [[Leroy Hill]] and starting rookie middle linebacker [[Bobby Wagner]].<ref>{{cite web| title=2012 Seattle Seahawks season preview part 4: The defensive depth chart| url=http://www.nwsportsbeat.com/seahawks/2012-seattle-defense-depth-chart-roster-analysis-7912/| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=nwsportsbeat.com| date=September 7, 2012| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180129141208/http://www.nwsportsbeat.com/seahawks/2012-seattle-defense-depth-chart-roster-analysis-7912/| archive-date=January 29, 2018| url-status=dead}}</ref> He took over play-calling duties from Hawthorne, who departed in free agency. He started the [[2012 Seattle Seahawks season|Seahawks']] season-opener against the [[2012 Arizona Cardinals season|Arizona Cardinals]] and recorded nine combined tackles and forced the first fumble of his career during a 20\u201316 loss. He forced running back [[Ryan Williams (American football)|Ryan Williams]] to fumble on the Cardinals' first drive and it was recovered by Seahawks' defensive lineman [[Brandon Mebane]].<ref>{{cite web| title=NFL Game Center: Week 1-2013: Seattle Seahawks @ Arizona Cardinals| url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2012090910/2012/REG1/seahawks@cardinals| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=nfl.com}}</ref> On September 24, 2012, Wright recorded a season-high 11 combined tackles during a 14\u201312 victory over the [[2012 Green Bay Packers season|Green Bay Packers]]. In Week 9, Wright left during the first quarter of a 30\u201320 win over the [[2012 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]] after suffering a [[concussion]].<ref>{{cite web| title=K.J. Wright injury report: Seahawks' leading tackler suffers concussion| url=http://www.sportingnews.com/nfl/news/4293529-kj-wright-injury-report-seahawks-lb-suffers-concussion| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=sportingnews.com| author=Danny O'Neil| date=November 5, 2012}}</ref> He was listed as inactive and remained in concussion protocol the following game. In Week 15, he made three combined tackles, deflected a pass, and intercepted quarterback [[Ryan Fitzpatrick]] as the Seahawks routed the [[2012 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]] 50\u201317. The next week, he collected seven combined tackles and sacked [[Alex Smith]] in a 42\u201313 defeat of the [[2012 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]]. He finished the {{NFL Year|2012}} season with 98 combined tackles (68 solo), five pass deflections, a sack, an interception, and a fumble recovery in 15 games and 15 starts.<ref name=\"stats2012\">{{cite web| title=NFL Player stats: K. J. Wright (2012)| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/k.j.wright/2495252/gamelogs?season=2012| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=nfl.com}}</ref> He played in 92% of the Seahawks' defensive snaps.<ref name=\"PFF\">{{cite web| title=How Seattle Seahawks Can Minimize the Loss of K.J. Wright| url=https://www.bleacherreport.com/amp/1888437-how-seattle-can-blunt-the-loss-of-kj-wright.amp.html| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=bleacherreport.com| author=Dan Matney| date=December 13, 2013}}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe Seahawks finished second in the [[NFC West]] with an 11\u20135 record and received a wildcard spot. On January 6, 2013, Wright started his first career playoff game and recorded eight combined tackles and a pass deflection during a 24\u201314 NFC Wildcard victory at the [[2012 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]]. They were eliminated from the playoffs the following week after losing 30\u201328 at the [[2012 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]] in the NFC Divisional round.<ref name=\"stats2012\"/>\n\n===2013===\nHead coach Carroll named Wagner, Wright, and [[Malcolm Smith (American football)|Malcolm Smith]] the starting linebackers to begin the regular season.<ref>{{cite web| title=Seattle Seahawks Roster 2013: Latest Cuts, Depth Charts and Analysis| url=https://www.bleacherreport.com/amp/1751013-seattle-seahawks-roster-2013-latest-cuts-depth-charts-and-analysis.amp.html| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=bleacherreport.com| author=Tyson Langland| date=August 27, 2013}}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> On September 15, 2013, Wright recorded six combined tackles, defended a pass, and sacked [[Colin Kaepernick]] as the Seahawks routed the [[2013 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]] 45\u201317. In Week 9, he collected a season-high 11 combined tackles during a 27\u201324 victory against the [[2013 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]]. On December 8, 2013, Wright made three combined tackles during a 19\u201317 loss at the San Francisco 49ers before leaving with a foot injury. It was later discovered to be a broken foot and Wright missed the remainder of the regular season.<ref>{{cite web| title=K.J. Wright injury: Seahawks LB out 6 weeks with broken foot| url=https://www.sbnation.com/platform/amp/nfl/2013/12/9/5191454/kj-wright-injury-update-seahawks| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=sbnation.com| author=Matt Verderame| date=December 9, 2013}}</ref> Wright finished the {{NFL Year|2013}} season with 80 combined tackles (46 solo), four pass deflections, and 1.5 sacks in 13 games and 13 starts.<ref name=\"stats2013\">{{cite web| title=NFL Player stats: K. J. Wright (2013)| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/k.j.wright/2495252/gamelogs?season=2013| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=nfl.com}}</ref> The Seahawks' defense allowed the fewest points during the season for the second consecutive season under defensive coordinator [[Gus Bradley]]. At the time of his injury, Wright's overall grade from [[Pro Football Focus]] ranked tenth among all outside linebackers.<ref>{{cite web| title=Wright (foot) to miss 4 to 6 weeks for Seahawks| url=https://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap2000000296121/article/kj-wright-foot-out-46-weeks-for-seattle-seahawks| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=NFL.com| author=Marc Sessler| date=December 10, 2013}}</ref> Wright played in 86% of Seattle's defensive snaps in 2013.<ref name=\"PFF\"/>\n\nThe Seahawks finished atop the NFC West with a 13\u20133 record. After defeating the [[2013 New Orleans Saints season|New Orleans Saints]], the Seahawks went on to face the San Francisco 49ers in the NFC Championship with Wright making his return from injury. He recorded two combined tackles as the Seahawks won 23\u201317. On February 2, 2014, Wright started in [[Super Bowl XLVIII]] and made seven combined tackles as they routed the [[2013 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]] 43\u20138.<ref name=\"stats2013\"/>\n\n===2014===\nOn December 18, 2014, the Seahawks signed Wright to a four-year, $27 million extension that included $10.18 million guaranteed and a signing bonus of $5 million.<ref name=\"spotrac\"/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://blogs.seattletimes.com/seahawks/2014/12/18/seahawks-sign-linebacker-k-j-wright-to-four-year-contract-extension/ | title=Seahawks sign linebacker K.J. Wright to four-year contract extension | first=Bob | last=Condotta | date=December 18, 2014 | work=The Seattle Times | accessdate=December 11, 2019}}</ref> He became the second-highest-paid outside linebacker behind only [[Lance Briggs]], and the contract had the largest total value of any outside linebacker's in the league.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://overthecap.com/position/4-3-outside-linebacker/ | title=4-3 Outside Linebacker Contracts | publisher=Over the Cap}}</ref>\n\nWright entered training camp slated as the starting weak side linebacker after defensive end [[Bruce Irvin (American football)|Bruce Irvin]] transitioned to strong side linebacker under new defensive coordinator [[Dan Quinn (American football)|Dan Quinn]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap2000000355206/article/seattle-seahawks-bruce-irvin-undergoes-hip-surgery |title=Seattle Seahawks' Bruce Irvin undergoes hip surgery |last=Wesseling |first=Chris  |date=June 2, 2014}}</ref> Head coach Carroll named Wright the starting weak side linebacker to start the regular season, opposite [[Mike Morgan (linebacker, born 1988)|Mike Morgan]], who was named the starting strong side linebacker while Irvin recuperated from hip surgery.<ref>{{cite web| title=Seahawks release updated depth chart| url=https://www.fieldgulls.com/platform/amp/2014/8/30/6088619/seahawks-updated-depth-chart-nfl-roster-cutdowns| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=fieldgulls.com| author=Danny Kelly| date=August 30, 2014}}</ref> On November 2, 2014, Weight recorded a season-high 13 combined tackles, a pass deflection, and a forced fumble during a 30\u201324 victory against the [[2014 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]]. In Week 13, he made seven combined tackles and recorded his first sack on the season on San Francisco 49ers' quarterback Colin Kaepernick in their 19\u20133 victory. Wright finished the {{NFL Year|2014}} season with 107 combined tackles (73 solo), four pass deflections, two sacks, and two forced fumbles in 16 games and 16 starts. It marked his first season with over 100 tackles and his first season starting all 16 games.<ref>{{cite web| title=NFL Player stats: K. J. Wright (2014)| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/k.j.wright/2495252/gamelogs?season=2014| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\nThe Seahawks finished atop the NFC West with a 12\u20134 record, marking their second consecutive season in first place. They went on to defeat the [[2014 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]] 31\u201317 and then defeated the [[2014 Green Bay Packers season|Green Bay Packers]] 28\u201322 to win the [[NFC Championship]]. On February 1, 2015, Wright recorded 11 combined tackles as the [[2014 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]] defeated the Seahawks 28\u201324 to win [[Super Bowl XLIX]].\n\n===2015===\nWright, Wagner, and Irvin returned to their starting roles in 2015 under new defensive coordinator [[Kris Richard]]. On September 20, 2015, Wright recorded nine combined tackles and forced a fumble during a 27\u201317 loss at the [[2015 Green Bay Packers season|Green Bay Packers]]. Wright was ejected from the game after getting into a physical altercation with Packers' tight end [[Richard Rodgers]] in the third quarter. Wright shoved Rodgers to the ground and attempted to rip his helmet off and was flagged for unnecessary roughness and immediately ejected from the game. On September 25, 2015, the NFL fined Wright $10,000 for the incident.<ref>{{cite web| title=Report: K.J. Wright fined for hit on Richard Rodgers| url=https://www.cbssports.com/college-football/news/report-k-j-wright-fined-for-hit-on-richard-rodgers/amp/| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=CBSSports.com| author=Derek Lewis| date=December 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn October 5, 2015, Wright was involved in a controversial play during a 13\u201310 win against the [[2015 Detroit Lions season|Detroit Lions]]. With less than two minutes remaining in the fourth quarter, Lions' wide receiver [[Calvin Johnson]] fumbled the ball at the one-yard line while attempting to dive in the end zone. Wright batted the ball out of the back of the endzone, resulting in a touchback and possession for the Seahawks. The play was scrutinized after ESPN officiating analyst Gerry Austin pointed out the error and explained that the referees failed to penalize Wright for illegal batting that would've given the Lions possession at the one-yard line. Wright admitted the bat was intentional, but was unaware of the penalty. The NFL vice-president of officiating Dean Blandino admitted fault on behalf of the referees and confirmed illegal batting, and that Wright should have been penalized.<ref>{{cite web| title=Seahawks' Wright didn't know rule, admits to intentionally batting fumble| url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2015/10/06/kj-wright-seahawks-lions-fumble-calvin-johnson| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=si.com| author=Peter Bukowski| date=October 6, 2015}}</ref> In Week 6, Wright recorded a season-high 12 combined tackles in the Seahawks' 27\u201323 loss to the [[2015 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]].\n\nThrough the first half of the 2015 season, Wright enjoyed the most productive stretch of his career, with 58 total tackles (34 solo), one tackle for loss, a forced fumble, a fumble recovery, and one pass defensed. Over these eight games, [[Pro Football Focus]] graded him as the second best linebacker in the league.<ref>https://www.profootballfocus.com/</ref> He finished the {{NFL Year|2015}} season with 115 combined tackles (71 solo), three pass deflections, and a sack in 16 games and 16 starts. He started all 16 games and had over 100 tackles for the second consecutive season.<ref>{{cite web| title=NFL Player stats: K. J. Wright (2015)| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/k.j.wright/2495252/gamelogs?season=2015| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref> [[Pro Football Focus]] ranked Wright 53rd among all players in 2015.<ref>{{cite web| title=PFF: Seahawks have three players in bottom of 50 of top 100| url=https://www.247sports.com/nfl/seattle-seahawks/Bolt/pff-seattle-seahawks-have-three-players-in-bottom-of-50-of-top-100-45271390/Amp| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=247sports.com| author=Derek Lewis| date=May 10, 2016}}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The Seahawks received a playoff berth after finishing second in the NFC West with a 10\u20136 record. After defeating the [[2015 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]], they went on to play the [[2015 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]] in the NFC Divisional round. Wright recorded 14 combined tackles as the Seahawks lost 31\u201324.\n\n===2016===\nDuring the offseason, strong side linebacker Bruce Irvin departed in free agency, while Wagner and Wright returned to their respective positions with [[Mike Morgan (linebacker, born 1988)|Mike Morgan]] taking over the vacant strong side linebacker role.<ref>{{cite web| title=Ourlads.com: Seattle Seahawks' depth chart: 10/01/2016| url=http://www.ourlads.com/nfldepthcharts/archive/188/SEA| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=ourlads.com}}</ref> Wright started the [[2016 Seattle Seahawks season|Seahawks']] season-opener against the [[2016 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]] and recorded a season-high 11 combined tackles and sacked quarterback [[Ryan Tannehill]] during a 12\u201310 victory. On October 23, 2016, he recorded a season-high ten solo tackles in the Seahawks' 6\u20136 tie with the [[2016 Arizona Cardinals season|Arizona Cardinals]]. He finished the {{NFL Year|2016}} season with a career-high 126 combined tackles (72 solo), five pass deflections, and a career-high four sacks in 16 games and 16 starts.<ref>{{cite web| title=NFL Player stats: K. J. Wright (2016)| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/k.j.wright/2495252/gamelogs?season=2016| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\nThe Seahawks finished 10\u20135\u20131 and first in the NFC West. On January 14, 2017, Wright recorded ten combined tackles in a 20\u201316 loss at the [[2016 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]]. Wright was selected as a replacement for [[Ryan Kerrigan]] for the [[2017 Pro Bowl]].<ref name=\"KerriganWright\">{{cite web | author=Boyle, John | date=January 17, 2017 | title=Seahawks K.J. Wright And Jimmy Graham Named To NFC Pro Bowl Team | work=seahawks.com | url=http://www.seahawks.com/news/2017/01/17/seahawks-kj-wright-and-jimmy-graham-named-nfc-pro-bowl-team | accessdate=March 4, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118150711/http://www.seahawks.com/news/2017/01/17/seahawks-kj-wright-and-jimmy-graham-named-nfc-pro-bowl-team | archive-date=January 18, 2017 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref> It was Wright's first Pro Bowl appearance. He finished the season with a career-high 126 tackles and four sacks.\n\n===2017===\nWright returned as the starting right outside linebacker, opposite [[Terence Garvin]]. On October 29, 2017, Wright recorded a season-high 15 combined tackles in the Seahawks' 41\u201338 victory against the [[2017 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]]. He missed a Week 15 matchup against the [[2017 Los Angeles Rams season|Los Angeles Rams]] due to a back injury.<ref>{{cite web| title=With K.J. Wright Back And Bobby Wagner \u201cFeeling A Lot Better,\u201d Seahawks Hope To See Defense Improve vs. Cowboys| url=http://www.seahawks.com/news/2017/12/20/kj-wright-back-and-bobby-wagner-\u201cfeeling-lot-better\u201d-seahawks-hope-see-defense| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=Seahawks.com| author=John Boyle| date=December 20, 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180128214337/http://www.seahawks.com/news/2017/12/20/kj-wright-back-and-bobby-wagner-%E2%80%9Cfeeling-lot-better%E2%80%9D-seahawks-hope-see-defense| archive-date=January 28, 2018| url-status=dead}}</ref> The injury ended his 53-game streak of starts. In Week 16, he made six combined tackles, deflected two passes, and intercepted a pass by [[Dak Prescott]] in a 21\u201312 victory at the [[2017 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]]. It was his first interception since 2012. He finished the season with 108 combined tackles (71 solo), six pass deflections, and an interception in 15 games and 15 starts. The Seahawks finished second in their division with a 9\u20137 record an did not qualify for the playoffs. It marked Wright's first time missing the playoffs with the Seahawks since his rookie season in 2011.<ref>{{cite web| title=NFL Player stats: K. J. Wright (2017)| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/k.j.wright/2495252/gamelogs| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=NFL.com}}</ref> Wright received an overall grade of 82.1 From [[Pro Football Focus]], ranking him 19th among all linebackers in 2017.<ref>{{cite web| title=Pro Football Focus: K. J. Wright| url=https://www.profootballfocus.com/nfl/players/kj-wright/6251| accessdate=January 29, 2018| website=profootballfocus.com}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018 ===\nWright suffered a knee injury in the final preseason game against the [[Minnesota Vikings]] and underwent [[Arthroscopy|arthroscopic knee surgery]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenewstribune.com/sports/nfl/seattle-seahawks/article217465940.html|title=Here\u2019s what Bobby Wagner knows about K.J. Wright\u2019s surgery, how much he values his Seahawks pal|work=thenewstribune|access-date=November 16, 2018|language=en}}</ref> As a result of the procedure, he missed the first six games of the season. Wright returned in week 8 against the [[Detroit Lions]] after the Seahawks' bye week, and recorded 5 solo tackles and a pass deflection in the 28\u201314 win.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2018102804/2018/REG8/seahawks@lions|title=Official Site of the National Football League {{!}} NFL.com|website=www.nfl.com|language=en-US|access-date=November 16, 2018}}</ref> The following week against the [[Los Angeles Chargers]], Wright recorded 7 combined tackles and another pass deflection in the 25\u201317 loss.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2018110408/2018/REG9/chargers@seahawks|title=Official Site of the National Football League {{!}} NFL.com|website=www.nfl.com|language=en-US|access-date=November 16, 2018}}</ref> Wright recorded 2 combined tackles against the [[Los Angeles Rams]] in week 10 but was forced to leave the game early in the second half after aggravating his knee injury.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/seahawks/bradley-mcdougald-made-it-through-the-entirety-of-seattles-defeat-to-the-rams-k-j-wright-did-not/|title=Bradley McDougald made it through the entirety of Seattle\u2019s defeat to the Rams. K.J. Wright did not.|date=November 11, 2018|work=The Seattle Times|access-date=November 16, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> He was inactive for the following week's game against the Green Bay Packers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theolympian.com/sports/nfl/seattle-seahawks/article221740060.html|title=Still-hurting K.J. Wright inactive. So are Seahawks Dion Jordan, forgotten C.J. Prosise|work=theolympian|access-date=November 16, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===2019===\nOn March 14, 2019, Wright signed a two-year, $15.5 million contract extension with the Seahawks.<ref>{{cite web|title=Seahawks Re-Sign Linebacker K.J. Wright|url=https://www.seahawks.com/news/seahawks-re-sign-linebacker-k-j-wright|author=Boyle, John|website=Seahawks.com|date=March 14, 2019}}</ref>\nIn week 3 against the [[New Orleans Saints]], Wright recorded 13 tackles in the 33\u201327 loss. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127993 |title=No Brees, no problem: Bridgewater, Saints top Seahawks 33-27 |date=22 September 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=22 September 2019}}</ref>\nIn week 6 against the [[Cleveland Browns]], Wright recorded an interception off [[Baker Mayfield]] in the 32\u201328 win. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128111 |title=Wilson's 3 TDs lead Seahawks' rally past Mayfield, Browns |date=13 October 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=13 October 2019}}</ref>\nIn week 15 against the [[Carolina Panthers]], Wright intercepted 2 passes thrown by [[Kyle Allen]] during the 30\u201324 win. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://sportsdata.usatoday.com/football/nfl/recap/76445 |title=Wilson leads Seahawks past Panthers |date=December 15, 2019 |website=www.sportsdata.usatoday.com |access-date=December 15, 2019}}</ref> Wright finished the season 11th in total tackles with 132.\n\n===NFL career statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" |Season